## Bulkhead Pattern

The Bulkhead pattern isolates failures by using **separate thread pools or connection pools** for different services — like bulkheads in a ship that prevent one flooded compartment from sinking the whole vessel.

```java
// Without bulkhead — one slow service starves all others
Executor sharedPool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(50);
// ServiceA, ServiceB, ServiceC all share 50 threads
// If ServiceC is slow → takes all 50 threads → A and B starve

// With bulkhead — isolated pools
Executor serviceAPool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(15);
Executor serviceBPool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(15);
Executor serviceCPool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(20);
// ServiceC slow → only its 20 threads affected → A and B still run
```

With Resilience4j:
```java
Bulkhead bulkhead = Bulkhead.of("paymentService", config -> config
    .maxConcurrentCalls(20)
    .maxWaitDuration(Duration.ofMillis(100)));

Supplier<String> decorated = Bulkhead.decorateSupplier(bulkhead, 
    () -> paymentService.charge(amount));
```

## Retry Strategies

Retries help with transient failures, but naive retries can make things worse.

```java
// Bad: immediate retry storm
for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    try { return callService(); }
    catch (Exception e) { /* retry immediately */ }
}

// Good: exponential backoff with jitter
int baseDelayMs = 100;
for (int attempt = 0; attempt < 3; attempt++) {
    try { return callService(); }
    catch (TransientException e) {
        long delay = baseDelayMs * (1L << attempt); // 100, 200, 400ms
        long jitter = (long)(Math.random() * delay); // ±50% random
        Thread.sleep(delay + jitter);
    }
}
```

**Jitter** prevents retry storms where all clients retry simultaneously after an outage.
